One can immediately see that the QNLS of speed meter has the same frequency dependence as the SQL at low frequencies, where quantum back-action noise dominates, which is a unique feature of the speed meters in general. It results from the back-action suppression, as expected from the QND speed measurement. However, it does not go parallel to the frequency axis, like, for instance, the frequency-dependent variational readout and the FQL do (see Fig. 8 in Sect. 3). One can see why on the two right panels of Fig. 21, where on the top plot, the quantum noise of the outgoing light phase quadrature (ϕLO=π/2\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
